# UK RMBS Capital Structure Analysis: Polaris 2025-3 vs. Competitors

## Executive Summary: Credit Enhancement Gap Analysis

|Transaction           |AAA CE|AAA Coverage|Buffer   |Key Driver                                          |
|----------------------|------|------------|---------|----------------------------------------------------|
|**Together 2025-1ST1**|10.00%|6.50%       |**3.50%**|Low LTV (60.1%) offsets high originator adj. (1.30x)|
|**Braccan 2025-2**    |11.75%|10.17%      |**1.58%**|Strong reserves + lower originator adj. (1.062x)    |
|**Polaris 2025-3**    |12.25%|10.88%      |**1.37%**|High WAFF (30.82%) from originator adj. (1.15x)     |
|**Elstree 2025-2**    |10.05%|9.57%       |**0.48%**|Most efficient - dual reserve structure + lower WAFF|

**Key Finding:** Polaris runs 89 bps higher CE than optimal peer Elstree, suggesting **50-75 bps of potential optimization** opportunity.

-----

## Part 1: Asset Quality Comparison

### Credit Assumptions Breakdown

|Metric             |Polaris 2025-3|Elstree 2025-2|Braccan 2025-2|Together 2025-1ST1|
|-------------------|--------------|--------------|--------------|------------------|
|**WAFF (AAA)**     |30.82%        |**24.78%** ✓  |23.65%        |20.98%            |
|**WALS (AAA)**     |35.30%        |38.60%        |42.99%        |**30.98%** ✓      |
|**Credit Coverage**|10.88%        |9.57%         |10.17%        |**6.50%** ✓       |
|**Original LTV**   |66.3%         |69.1%         |71.2%         |**60.1%** ✓       |
|**Current LTV**    |66.4%         |69.2%         |70.2%         |**58.5%** ✓       |
|**Seasoning**      |2 mo          |3.6 mo        |11 mo         |**17 mo** ✓       |
|**Arrears ≥1mo**   |**0.04%** ✓   |0.7%          |3.2%          |3.2%              |

### WAFF Build-Up Analysis (AAA Level)

**Critical Driver: Originator Adjustment**

|Transaction           |Originator Adj.|Impact on WAFF|Rationale from Report                                                                       |
|----------------------|---------------|--------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
|**Polaris 2025-3**    |**1.15x**      |+4.02%        |Prefunding (24.3%) + low ‘B’ WAFF (3.88%) vs. historical performance + nonconforming lending|
|**Elstree 2025-2**    |1.075x         |+1.73%        |“Not PRA-regulated, lack of experience in owner-occupied field”                             |
|**Braccan 2025-2**    |1.062x         |+1.35%        |“Not PRA-regulated for BTL + specialist nonbank lender”                                     |
|**Together 2025-1ST1**|**1.30x**      |+6.40%        |Elevated 90+ arrears + historical performance + nonconforming focus                         |

**Analysis:** Polaris’s 1.15x originator adjustment is **punitive** given:

1. UK Mortgage Lending has 10-year track record (comparable to Elstree’s originator Enra)
1. Strong historical performance (arrears below 6.0%, better than nonconforming index)
1. Only 5 losses recorded since 2015 (max 18% severity)
1. **But:** The 24.3% prefunding and very low 2-month seasoning are penalized

-----

## Part 2: Structural Feature Comparison

### Reserve & Liquidity Structures

|Feature                      |Polaris 2025-3                     |Elstree 2025-2 ⭐                   |Braccan 2025-2                     |Together 2025-1ST1                 |
|-----------------------------|-----------------------------------|-----------------------------------|-----------------------------------|-----------------------------------|
|**Liquidity Reserve**        |Higher of 1% A or B (unfunded)     |1% of A+B (unfunded)               |1% of A+B (facility then reserve)  |Facility then 1.1% A+B             |
|**General Reserve**          |None                               |**1% of A-E (non-amortizing)**     |**0.35% of rated notes**           |None                               |
|**Reserve Funding**          |Principal receipts                 |Principal then revenue             |Fully funded at close              |Facility at close                  |
|**Principal to Pay Interest**|A always; B-G when senior + PDL<10%|A always; B-E when senior + PDL<10%|A always; B-D when senior + PDL<10%|A always; B-E when senior + PDL<10%|

**Key Insight:** Elstree’s **dual reserve structure** (liquidity + general) provides superior protection:

- General reserve available for ALL rated notes (A-D)
- Non-amortizing = permanent credit enhancement
- This structural efficiency allows **tighter initial CE**

### Waterfall Comparison

**Critical Differences in Revenue Waterfall:**

|Position         |Polaris 2025-3                                                     |Elstree 2025-2                                                   |Impact                                                        |
|-----------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------|
|After Class A PDL|Class B interest<br>→ **Liquidity reserve top-up**<br>→ Class B PDL|Class B interest<br>→ **General reserve top-up**<br>→ Class B PDL|Elstree’s general reserve is<br>senior to junior note interest|
|Reserve Priority |Liquidity reserve for A+B only                                     |General reserve available for<br>**all rated notes A-E**         |Better liquidity for all tranches                             |

-----

## Part 3: Key Drivers of CE Gap

### Why Polaris Requires Higher CE

|Factor                           |Impact                                 |Quantification|Optimization Opportunity                            |
|---------------------------------|---------------------------------------|--------------|----------------------------------------------------|
|**1. High Originator Adjustment**|+2.3% WAFF vs. Elstree                 |~60-75 bps CE |✓ Address through historical data, reduce prefunding|
|**2. No General Reserve**        |Structural inefficiency                |~35 bps CE    |✓ Add 0.5-1.0% general reserve                      |
|**3. Shared Ownership (7.52%)**  |Higher LTV adjustment (1.296x vs 1.08x)|~30 bps CE    |Limited - collateral feature                        |
|**4. Low Seasoning (2 mo)**      |Limited track record                   |~20 bps CE    |✓ Select more seasoned loans                        |
|**5. Unfunded Liquidity Reserve**|Initial liquidity exposure             |~15 bps CE    |✓ Fund at closing or use facility                   |

**Total Optimization Potential: 50-75 bps at AAA level**

-----

## Part 4: Detailed Optimization Recommendations

### Recommendation 1: Reduce Originator Adjustment (40-50 bps savings)

**Current Penalty Drivers:**

- **Prefunding (24.3%):** S&P states “we increased our originator adjustment to cover additional prefunding risks”
- **Low ‘B’ WAFF:** 3.88% is below typical nonconforming (Together at 3.32%, but with much lower LTV)

**Action Plan:**

```
A. Reduce prefunding to 10-15% maximum
   - Provides certainty on pool composition
   - Reduces "migration risk" to eligibility limits
   - Elstree had 0% prefunding
   
B. Include more seasoned loans
   - Current: 2 months WA
   - Target: 6-12 months WA
   - Demonstrates performance through at least one payment cycle
   
C. Strengthen R&W package
   - Polaris has "no sunset clause" (positive)
   - But add specific representations on:
     * Shared ownership documentation quality
     * Valuation methodology for complex properties
     * Income verification standards
```

### Recommendation 2: Implement Dual Reserve Structure (30-40 bps savings)

**Model: Elstree’s Approach**

```
Liquidity Reserve:
- Size: 1.0% of Class A + B balance
- Purpose: Cover senior fees + A/B interest shortfalls
- Funding: Unfunded at close, builds via principal
- Amortizing: Yes

General Reserve (NEW):
- Size: 0.50-0.75% of Class A-E balance  
- Purpose: Credit enhancement for ALL rated notes
- Funding: Fully funded at closing
- Amortizing: No
- Available for: Senior fees, interest, PDL reduction

Benefits:
1. Permanent CE boost for all tranches
2. Better liquidity coverage for junior notes
3. Reduced reliance on principal borrowing
4. Comparable to Braccan (0.35%) and Elstree (1.0%) structures
```

**Cost-Benefit:**

- Upfront cost: £3.3M (0.75% × £440M pool)
- CE reduction: 30-40 bps across structure
- NPV positive if spread pricing improves by >15 bps

### Recommendation 3: Optimize Collateral Selection (20-30 bps savings)

**Target Pool Characteristics:**

|Metric               |Current |Target         |Rationale                                                      |
|---------------------|--------|---------------|---------------------------------------------------------------|
|**WA Seasoning**     |2 months|**8-12 months**|Align with Polaris 2025-2 (8 mo); demonstrates payment history |
|**Shared Ownership** |7.52%   |**<5%**        |Reduce to Polaris 2022-2 level (0.81%); lower LTV adjustment   |
|**Interest-Only**    |10.9%   |**<8%**        |Reduce owner-occupied IO exposure; lower adjustment            |
|**First-Time Buyers**|31.1%   |**<25%**       |Reduce unseasoned first-time buyer concentration               |
|**CCJ Borrowers**    |20.1%   |**<15%**       |While not unusual for nonconforming, reduce higher-risk segment|

**Impact Modeling:**

```
Shared Ownership reduction: 7.52% → 5.0%
- LTV adjustment: 1.296x → 1.20x
- WAFF reduction: ~1.5%
- CE impact: ~20 bps

First-time buyer reduction: 31.1% → 25%  
- FTB adjustment: 1.03x → 1.025x
- WAFF reduction: ~0.3%
- CE impact: ~5 bps

Interest-only reduction: 10.9% → 7%
- IO adjustment: 1.02x → 1.015x  
- WAFF reduction: ~0.2%
- CE impact: ~5 bps
```

### Recommendation 4: Alternative Liquidity Structures (15-20 bps savings)

**Option A: Liquidity Facility at Closing (Model: Braccan/Together)**

```
Structure:
- Facility provider: Wells Fargo / Lloyds / HSBC
- Size: 1.1% of A+B notes (higher of £)
- Commitment fee: 100 bps on undrawn
- Drawn margin: SONIA + 90 bps (pre-step), +190 bps (post-step)
- Availability: Day 1

Benefits:
- Immediate liquidity coverage
- S&P views positively: "liquidity source available at closing"
- Removes "unfunded reserve" concern from rating analysis
- Transition to funded reserve post step-up

Costs:
- £4.4M × 1.0% = £44k annually (commitment fee)
- But saves upfront reserve funding and improves pricing
```

**Option B: Fund Liquidity Reserve at Closing**

```
- Fully fund 1% A+B at closing (£4.0M)
- Source: Seller contribution or note proceeds
- Benefit: Removes S&P concern about initial liquidity exposure
- Trade-off: Upfront cash vs. structural efficiency
```

-----

## Part 5: Competitor Strengths & Weaknesses

### Elstree 2025-2 (Best-in-Class Structure) ⭐

**Strengths:**

1. **Optimal reserve structure:** Dual reserves (liquidity + general) provide maximum efficiency
1. **Lower originator penalty:** 1.075x vs. Polaris 1.15x despite also being non-PRA regulated
1. **Balanced collateral:** 49% BTL / 51% owner-occupied provides diversification
1. **Standby servicer:** BCMGlobal in place day-one (operational risk mitigation)

**Weaknesses:**

1. Higher LTV than Polaris (69.2% vs. 66.4%)
1. Higher arrears (0.7% vs. 0.04%)
1. Higher WALS (38.6% vs. 35.3%)

**Why Elstree Achieves Lower CE Despite Weaknesses:**

- Structural efficiency (reserves) + lower originator penalty **offsets** weaker collateral metrics
- Key learning: **Structure matters as much as collateral**

### Braccan 2025-2 (Strong BTL Specialist)

**Strengths:**

1. **Low originator penalty:** 1.062x (lowest of peer group)
1. **Seasoned collateral:** 11 months WA seasoning
1. **General reserve:** 0.35% provides permanent CE
1. **Paratus track record:** 8 private + 7 public securitizations

**Weaknesses:**

1. **Higher arrears:** 3.2% (73x higher than Polaris)
1. **Higher LTV:** 71.2% original, 70.2% current
1. **High multifamily exposure:** 9.7% HMOs/MUBs
1. **Very high WALS:** 42.99% (highest in peer group)

**Why CE is Higher:**

- WALS drives credit coverage requirement
- But strong reserves + low originator adjustment contain the gap

### Together 2025-1ST1 (High Buffer, Different Strategy)

**Strengths:**

1. **Very low LTV:** 60.1% original, 58.5% current (best-in-class)
1. **Strong seasoning:** 17 months WA
1. **Liquidity facility:** Available day 1
1. **Lowest WALS:** 30.98% due to high equity

**Weaknesses:**

1. **Highest originator penalty:** 1.30x (weak historical arrears)
1. **High arrears:** 3.2% current, historical 90+ elevated
1. **Highest CCJ exposure:** Not disclosed but implied in 1.30x adjustment
1. **Complex borrower base:** Requires higher WAFF

**Why Buffer is Largest (3.50%):**

- Conservative structure accounts for originator risk
- Low LTV offsets high default probability
- Additional buffer provides marketing/distribution advantage

-----

## Part 6: Optimal Capital Structure for New Polaris

### Proposed Structure

|Class     |Current CE|Optimized CE|Δ      |Coverage|Buffer|Key Changes                         |
|----------|----------|------------|-------|--------|------|------------------------------------|
|**A**     |12.25%    |**11.50%**  |-75 bps|10.50%  |1.00% |Reserve structure + lower orig. adj.|
|**B-Dfrd**|6.75%     |**6.25%**   |-50 bps|6.00%   |0.25% |Structural efficiency               |
|**C-Dfrd**|3.50%     |**3.25%**   |-25 bps|3.20%   |0.05% |Maintained for stability            |
|**D-Dfrd**|1.75%     |**1.75%**   |-      |1.70%   |0.05% |No change (tight already)           |

**Capital Structure Sizing (on £440M pool):**

```
Class A:     £389.2M (88.50%) - was 87.75%
Class B-Dfrd: £23.1M (5.25%) - was 5.50%  
Class C-Dfrd: £13.2M (3.00%) - was 3.25%
Class D-Dfrd: £7.7M (1.75%) - unchanged
Class E-G:    As current structure
```

**Reserve Structure:**

```
Liquidity Reserve:
- Size: 1.0% of Class A + B (£4.1M)
- Funding: Day 1 facility (SONIA+90bps), transition to funded reserve
- Amortizing: Yes, with A+B notes
- Available for: A and B notes when senior

General Reserve (NEW):
- Size: 0.60% of Class A-E rated notes (£2.6M)  
- Funding: Funded at closing
- Amortizing: No
- Available for: All rated notes A-E, fees, PDL reduction
- Priority: After liquidity reserve in revenue waterfall
```

### Expected Rating Outcomes

**S&P Analysis:**

|Factor             |Current Impact|Optimized Impact|Change                                             |
|-------------------|--------------|----------------|---------------------------------------------------|
|**WAFF (AAA)**     |30.82%        |**29.20%**      |-1.62% via lower originator adj. & better seasoning|
|**WALS (AAA)**     |35.30%        |**35.00%**      |-0.30% via lower shared ownership                  |
|**Credit Coverage**|10.88%        |**10.22%**      |Reduced due to lower WAFF                          |
|**Available CE**   |12.25%        |**12.10%**      |Structural CE via general reserve                  |
|**Buffer**         |1.37%         |**1.88%**       |Increased despite lower note CE                    |

**Rating Confidence:**

- **AAA:** High confidence - 1.88% buffer vs. 1.37% current
- **AA:** Maintained - sufficient cushion remains
- **Lower ratings:** Benefit from general reserve support

